          "tool_use_id": "toolu_01Htd8bCGwwdmLAPzfu7uWeK",
          "type": "tool_result",
          "content": "# Etymology of Defenestration\n\n**Root Language:** Latin\n\n**Root Components:**\n- *de-* (\"down, off, away from\")\n- *fenestra* (\"window, opening for light\")\n\n**First Use:** 1620\n\n**Origin Story:**\nThe word was \"invented for one incident: the 'Defenestration of Prague' (May 21, 1618),\" in which Protestant radicals threw Catholic deputies and a secretary from a castle window. The trio unexpectedly survived by landing in a trash heap, an event that sparked the Thirty Years' War.\n\nThe Latin term *fenestra* is believed to derive from Etruscan, based on linguistic patterns seen in other Latin borrowings containing the suffix *-(s)tra*."
        }
      ]
    },
